article.headline: 39-year-old Rocket scores 25 points
article.linkText: Rockets gain 7th seed without Francis, Mobley
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- At 39, Mark Jackson still has enough in the tank to help fuel the Rockets. Jackson made a rare start and scored a season-high 25 points in Houston's 111-107 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Monday night. The win helped the Rockets lock up the seventh seed in the Western Conference playoffs. "I just do basically what is asked of me," said Jackson, who signed with Houston as a free agent on Jan. 15. "Fortunately, I was able to make some shots and step up and play well tonight. I just thank God that at 39 I can go out there and play a kid's game and be effective. It's a blessing." He entered the game with a 1.9-point scoring average and had made only three of his 33 3-point attempts this season. He made three from beyond the arc and shot 14-of-17 from the free throw line. Jackson scored all six of his fourth-quarter points at the line in the final 1:37. Houston has won three of its last four games, while Seattle has dropped seven of nine. The Rockets were outstanding from 3-point range, making 14 of 27. "When that team is shooting like that on the perimeter and attacking your rotation, they're a tough team to beat," Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. The Rockets aren't playing great right now, but they're getting closer to being on track for the playoffs. Jackson feels the Rockets will give teams problems in the postseason. "We won't just be happy getting through the first round," Jackson said. "We're talking about moving on. I think we can create havoc in this playoff picture." Six Rockets reached double figures. Yao Ming had 20 points, Jim Jackson scored 18 of his 22 points in the first quarter, Maurice Taylor had 16, Scott Padgett added 12 and Bostjan Nachbar had 11. The Rockets were without their usual starting guard tandem of Steve Francis and Cuttino Mobley. Francis has been suffering from a sprained right wrist and inflammation in his left elbow. Mobley has a left shoulder contusion, which he got while setting a pick at Utah on Saturday. Houston led 81-61 with 4:54 to play in the third quarter, but the Sonics made a furious run in the fourth quarter. Seattle made three straight 3-pointers, one each by Vladimir Radmanovic, Ray Allen and Rashard Lewis, before Lewis caught a fast-break lob from Ronald Murray for a dunk that trimmed Houston's advantage to 98-94 with 3:45 to play. Nachbar hit a 3-pointer with 30.9 left. Radmanovic responded with another 3-pointer with 12.8 to make it 105-103. Rockets coach Jeff Van Gundy was pleased with how Nachbar had the confidence to take the big shot in a clutch situation. "To have the courage to step up and that that shot is very good," Van Gundy said. Mark Jackson and Jim Jackson combined to make five free throws in the final 12 seconds to keep the Rockets in front. Van Gundy may have been most pleased with the energy of his team after the Rockets had a terrible effort against Utah on Saturday and scored only 69 points -- the fifth-lowest total in franchise history. The Rockets opened the game with an 18-3 run. In the second half, Houston outscored Seattle 25-8 in the first seven minutes of the third quarter. "In both halves, we came out ready," Van Gundy said. "I was proud of our guys for that." The Sonics were led by Murray's 24 points. Allen and Radmanovic had 21 points apiece. Vitaly Potapenko added 12 and Lewis 11.< ^Notes@: Before the game, a small plane flying over downtown Seattle had a banner trailing behind it that read: Go Sonics - Fire Wally Walker!, referring to the team's president. ... Seattle placed F Leon Smith on the injured list with a sprained left ankle. He was replaced by Radmanovic, who had been on the injured list since April 2 with a sprained right ankle. ... The Sonics were 21-20 at home, their worst home winning percentage since going 20-21 in 1984-85. ... Houston F Kelvin Cato did not play. Nachbar made his second start of the season.
